    <text id="R137706072T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>In early June, 1864, Union forces occupied Staunton, VA. In this dispatch, the
                    Union Provost Marshall stationed in Staunton notifies General William Averell of
                    guidelines for troops while in and near town. Averell is asked to post guards to
                    prevent marauding, see that all soldiers entering town have a pass, and to send
                    officers with men coming to town to shoe their horses.</p>
            </div1>
        </front>
        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
                <head>
                    OFFICE PROVOST-MARSHAL-GEN.,<lb/> HDQRS. DEPARTMENT OF WEST VIRGINIA,
                    <name type="recipient">Brig.-Gen. AVERELL,<lb/> Cmdg. Cavalry Division:</name>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1864-06-08">June 8, 1864.</date>
                        <name type="place">Staunton, Va.,</name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute>GEN.:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>You will see that all private property and dwellings in the vicinity of your camp
                    has a guard, to prevent soldiers from marauding. No soldier will be allowed to
                    enter the town without a pass from division headquarters. When horses are sent
                    into town to be shod they must be sent under the charge of a commissioned
                    officer.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>By order of Maj.-Gen. Hunter:</salute>
                    <signed>D. H. HARKINS,<lb/> Maj. and Acting Provost-Marshal-Gen.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
